V<<sidebar "How to get a travel visa">>\u000aA ''travel visa'' is not a credit card! It's a stamp or sticker placed in your passport that allows you to enter a foreign country. Depending on your own nationality and your reasons for traveling, ''you may or may not need a visa'' to visit a given country.\u000a\u000a<<if $facultyled>>Faculty-led courses abroad will generally require only a tourist visa, or for US passport holders many will require no visa at all. However, if<<else>>If<</if>> you will be taking classes from an institution based in your host country, you will usually need a student-class visa to enter. Entry requirements are often lower when you are simply visiting as a tourist.<<if $facultyled>> If you aren't sure whether you need a student-class visa, talk with your faculty leader.\u000a\u000a''If you will not be traveling on a US passport'', you may have different entry requirements from others traveling on your program. It is your responsibility to be aware of these requirements and obtain required visa(s). GEO can help get your oriented to the process. \u000a\u000a<</if>> Requirements to get a visa may include photographs, financial information, a letter from your host university, a criminal background check, an HIV test, or even a personal appearance at the foreign consulate. Your own nationality may have a major impact on the requirements you face in getting a visa. For example, US citizens typically face lower barriers than students of other nationalities. \u000a\u000aIn certain cases, students may be able to enter a country without a visa, but will need to obtain a ''residence permit'' after entering.\u000a\u000aIf you have traveled often internationally, be aware that your visa may ''require one or more blank pages in your passport book''. If you don't have at least two completely blank pages in your passport, check on the requirements for your specific destination(s) as soon as possible.\u000a\u000a''Your <<if $facultyled>>program leader should<<else>>study abroad provider will<</if>> inform you'' about your visa requirements. If you are uncertain or have general questions, please contact <<if $facultyled>>your program administration (see below)<<else>>GEO<</if>>. \u000a\u000a|box|k\u000a|>|!Further information|\u000a|[[Travisa|http://www.travisa.com/]]|Easy access to visa requirements for all countries and most nationalities|\u000a|[[Visa @Wikipedia|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visa_(document)]]|Article providing information about visa policies around the world|\u000a\u000a<<if $facultyled>><<display "Faculty-Led Administration">>\u000a<</if>>\u005c\u000a<<segue "Passport Check">>
